03:08.980 --> 03:11.221
Um, listen, you take 'em.
I don't need 'em.

03:11.233 --> 03:13.224
No, no, no.
You saw them first. I...

03:13.235 --> 03:14.600
Please. I insist.

03:14.611 --> 03:15.817
I mean, here. Take 'em.

03:16.822 --> 03:18.107
- Oh, oh!
Hey, wait a minute.

03:18.115 --> 03:19.275
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa!
Hey!

03:19.282 --> 03:20.442
- Excuse me, sir.
- Yeah?

03:20.450 --> 03:22.406
- These are ours.
- Oh. Your gloves?

03:22.411 --> 03:23.491
- Yes.
- Well, how come? I mean...

03:23.495 --> 03:26.658
They're just sort of hanging there,
sleeping with their little price tag on.

03:26.665 --> 03:28.530
We were just discussing them, all right?
This is, uh...

03:28.542 --> 03:30.203
Well, I have news for you.

03:30.210 --> 03:32.872
You can go on discussing them
long after I've paid for them.

03:32.879 --> 03:34.164
Calm down, all right?
Just calm down.

03:34.172 --> 03:35.912
Calm down?
It's five days before Christmas.

03:35.924 --> 03:37.414
I'm in the middle of a New York
department store.

03:37.426 --> 03:38.586
He's asking me to calm down.

03:38.593 --> 03:41.676
Well, listen. These were meant to be
a very special gift for someone.

03:41.680 --> 03:43.216
Yeah, we've put quite a lot
of thought into those.

03:43.223 --> 03:44.429
- Ah.
- Isn't that right?

03:44.433 --> 03:46.139
Who are you?
And who were they for?

03:46.143 --> 03:47.178
- My boyfriend.
- My girlfriend.

03:47.644 --> 03:50.852
- His girlfriend.
- Her boyfriend.

03:50.981 --> 03:52.721
One pair of gloves for two people?

03:52.816 --> 03:54.556
- This is hard to explain.
- Well, try.

03:54.568 --> 03:56.104
All right. Go ahead.

03:57.070 --> 04:01.905
Oh. Uh, well, he is at the present time
my boyfriend.

04:03.076 --> 04:04.566
But in 18 months...

04:05.912 --> 04:07.243
after the operation...

04:10.250 --> 04:11.831
- he will be...
- she will be...

04:12.210 --> 04:14.997
...my girlfriend.
Do you understand?

04:15.589 --> 04:16.920
That didn't really work out.

04:16.923 --> 04:19.380
- No, but Merry Christmas anyway.
- Thank you very much.

04:19.384 --> 04:20.248
All right.

04:20.886 --> 04:24.253
Well, you earned these.
That was quick on your feet.

04:24.264 --> 04:27.472
- Thanks. It was a team effort.
- Yeah, it was. It was.

04:28.268 --> 04:30.350
- I don't know how to thank you.
- Well...

04:30.604 --> 04:31.844
Ah, well.

04:32.272 --> 04:34.854
♪ And have a Yule that's cool ♪

04:36.234 --> 04:37.223
They're ready for you guys.

04:37.235 --> 04:38.350
Thank you.

04:38.987 --> 04:41.228
I don't know if what you said to that guy
makes any sense.

04:41.323 --> 04:43.279
It was helpful. I think we scared
the bejesus out of him.

04:43.283 --> 04:44.272
Oh, you were pretty fierce.

04:44.910 --> 04:46.946
This will work, though.
This is quite a coffee.

04:47.120 --> 04:48.781
No, but I'm serious about the check.

04:48.789 --> 04:49.778
It's the least I can do.

04:49.790 --> 04:52.452
Well, thank you, but, see,

04:52.459 --> 04:55.747
now I have to go find something else
for my girlfriend.

04:55.754 --> 04:58.120
- Oh, they were for your girlfriend.
- Yes, they were.

04:58.590 --> 05:00.296
Oh, I can't accept them then.

05:00.300 --> 05:01.460
Well, you have to.
Otherwise you won't treat.

05:01.468 --> 05:02.674
Really.

05:02.928 --> 05:05.260
Let me tell you something.
This is the ultimate blended drink.

05:05.639 --> 05:06.924
Where did you find this place?

05:06.932 --> 05:08.513
I first came in because of the name.

05:08.517 --> 05:09.757
- Hmm.
- Serendipity.

05:09.768 --> 05:11.474
- It's one of my favorite words.
- It is?

05:11.478 --> 05:12.718
- Uh-huh.
- Why?

05:13.021 --> 05:14.761
'Cause it's such a nice sound for what it means:

05:14.773 --> 05:16.309
A fortunate accident.

05:16.608 --> 05:18.724
- Mm.
- Except I don't really believe in accidents.

05:18.735 --> 05:20.441
I think fate's behind everything.

05:20.445 --> 05:21.355
Oh, you do?

05:21.363 --> 05:23.149
- Yeah.
- Fate's behind everything?

05:23.532 --> 05:24.738
Well, I think so.

05:24.741 --> 05:26.697
Everything's predestined?
We don't have any choice at all?

05:27.160 --> 05:28.650
No, I think we make our own decisions.

05:28.662 --> 05:31.119
I just think that fate sends us little signs,

05:31.122 --> 05:32.202
and it's how we read the signs

05:32.207 --> 05:33.617
that determines whether we're happy or not.

05:33.625 --> 05:35.035
Little signals.

05:35.043 --> 05:36.408
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

05:36.419 --> 05:38.705
Fortunate accidents.
Lucky discoveries.

05:38.713 --> 05:40.203
Like Columbus and America.

05:40.215 --> 05:42.797
Yeah, or Fleming discovering...

05:42.801 --> 05:44.132
- ...penicillin.
- Penicillin. Yeah.

05:44.594 --> 05:46.130
- Fleming is his name?
- Yes.

05:46.137 --> 05:47.422
Or "Jonathan and the Gloves."

05:48.640 --> 05:49.800
I don't know that one.

05:49.808 --> 05:52.174
You don't know that story?
It's an old folk tale. Classic.

05:52.561 --> 05:55.223
Our hero, Jonathan, goes out
in search of black gloves.

05:55.230 --> 05:58.188
And in a perfect act of serendipiocity

05:58.191 --> 05:59.727
or serendipaciousness,

05:59.734 --> 06:03.397
he runs into a beautiful,
attractive English girl

06:03.405 --> 06:04.394
with a boyfriend.

06:05.407 --> 06:06.522
You have a boyfriend, right?

06:07.117 --> 06:08.903
- Yeah, I do.
- That's what I thought.

06:08.910 --> 06:10.446
And you have the glove lady.

06:10.453 --> 06:11.784
Yes, I do.

06:14.249 --> 06:16.205
- Mm-hmm.
- It was a very nice time.

06:20.380 --> 06:22.120
Well, I hope you enjoy the gloves
you bought yourself.

06:22.132 --> 06:23.338
Oh, I'm sure I will.

06:23.341 --> 06:25.332
I usually appreciate my own thoughtfulness.

06:26.595 --> 06:27.550
What do you want for Christmas?

06:27.554 --> 06:29.419
- Golf clubs.
- Oh.

06:30.140 --> 06:31.755
So you're gonna meet your boyfriend now or what?

06:31.766 --> 06:34.348
No, I think he's probably out
doing what you're doing.

06:34.769 --> 06:36.475
Getting a crush on someone else's girlfriend?

06:37.647 --> 06:39.603
No, I'm sorry. I just meant to say
that I had a really great time, and...

06:39.608 --> 06:42.395
Um...you know, maybe you should
give me your phone number,

06:42.402 --> 06:43.437
you know, just in case.

06:43.445 --> 06:46.107
- In case of what?
- You know, in case of life.

06:46.615 --> 06:49.072
I just had a great time,
and I'd never be able to find you again.

06:49.659 --> 06:51.775
Well, if we're meant to meet again, then...

06:51.786 --> 06:52.821
we'll meet again.

06:52.829 --> 06:54.490
It's just not the right time now.

06:54.497 --> 06:56.112
Maybe we were supposed to meet on British time

06:56.124 --> 06:58.080
- and we're five hours too early.

06:58.084 --> 07:00.245
Come on.
I don't even know your name.

07:00.253 --> 07:01.834
My name is Jonathan.

07:02.422 --> 07:03.878
Does that make you wanna tell me something?

07:04.466 --> 07:05.751
Yeah, it does.

07:07.510 --> 07:10.297
Merry Christmas, Jonathan.
And thanks.

07:17.687 --> 07:18.676
That's it?!

07:19.731 --> 07:21.892
♪ I can feel my heart ♪

07:23.777 --> 07:25.392
- Oh, Jesus, I'm sorry.
- ♪ And it's fit to burst ♪

07:25.403 --> 07:26.483
I'm sorry about that.

07:27.364 --> 07:29.776
# I try to clean it up ♪

07:31.326 --> 07:33.942
♪ But I just get worse ♪

07:35.205 --> 07:37.571
♪ Wish I could fall ♪

07:39.167 --> 07:41.203
♪ On a night like this ♪

07:42.921 --> 07:45.833
- ♪ Into your loving arms ♪
- I think I left a scarf.

07:45.840 --> 07:48.081
No. Nothing down here.
Why don't you go upstairs?

07:48.301 --> 07:49.632
- Maybe it's still there.
- Thank you.

07:50.470 --> 07:53.257
♪ I thought I saw your face ♪

07:54.641 --> 07:56.677
♪ In the evening sky ♪

07:58.436 --> 08:00.848
♪ On a lonesome cloud ♪

08:02.357 --> 08:04.518
♪ That was drifting by ♪

08:05.986 --> 08:08.318
♪ I wish I could fall ♪

08:10.073 --> 08:11.904
♪ On a night like this ♪

08:13.910 --> 08:16.401
♪ Into your loving arms ♪

08:17.455 --> 08:18.285
Hey.

08:19.499 --> 08:20.329
Hey.

08:27.757 --> 08:28.917
Let's go do something.

08:29.926 --> 08:31.791
All right.
What you wanna do?

08:31.803 --> 08:33.634
I don't care.

08:34.764 --> 08:35.970
All right. Come on.

08:47.986 --> 08:49.726
Now, promise me you're not just
visiting here for a week

08:49.738 --> 08:52.104
or marrying somebody to get a green card or...

08:52.449 --> 08:53.939
on parole.

08:54.701 --> 08:57.317
None of the above. You?

08:57.328 --> 08:59.910
No, no, no. Proud U.S. citizen.
No criminal record.

08:59.914 --> 09:02.747
So you won't tell me your name.
Well, tell me, uh...

09:03.334 --> 09:05.370
what do you miss most about Mother England?

09:05.378 --> 09:06.584
I miss my mom terribly.

09:07.756 --> 09:09.462
If I were her, I'd miss you too.

09:16.848 --> 09:20.090
Okay. Favorite movie.

09:21.102 --> 09:23.218
The correct answer is
<i>Cool Hand Luke.</i>

09:23.563 --> 09:24.598
I've never seen it.

09:24.606 --> 09:26.562
Oh, come on.
You've never seen <i>Cool Hand Luke?</i>

09:27.484 --> 09:30.692
Paul Newman?
Oh, my God. Come on!

09:31.196 --> 09:34.279
"Failure to communicate,"
sadistic cop in sunglasses with no name.

09:34.574 --> 09:36.565
- Reminds me of you in that way.

09:36.576 --> 09:39.033
Um, favorite New York moment.

09:43.291 --> 09:44.997
This one's climbing the charts.

09:46.086 --> 09:47.326
I'm flattered.

09:49.547 --> 09:51.378
Is there anything else you need
to know about me?

09:52.425 --> 09:53.460
Huh.

09:55.678 --> 09:57.134
Favorite sexual position?

09:58.014 --> 09:59.675
Oh!

10:00.183 --> 10:01.764
Whoa! Whoa! Whoa!

10:02.060 --> 10:04.597
Yeah, yeah.
That's my favorite too.

10:05.230 --> 10:06.436
- You all right?
- Yeah.

10:06.439 --> 10:07.849
- Did you hurt yourself?
- No.

10:07.857 --> 10:08.721
- Yes, a little.
- You did?

10:08.733 --> 10:10.348
- Ouch.
- Oh, let's take a look at that.

10:11.111 --> 10:12.772
Oh, Jesus. Wow.

10:13.196 --> 10:14.982
- That's a deep, deep gash.
- Gaping.

10:15.573 --> 10:16.562
- What?

10:17.492 --> 10:19.107
Well, we'll fix that right up.

10:20.912 --> 10:21.992
There you go.

10:25.250 --> 10:26.160
What?

10:27.502 --> 10:28.867
Oh, you're looking at my freckles?

10:29.587 --> 10:31.293
It's the curse of the English, I'm afraid.

10:31.464 --> 10:33.921
- Fair skin and bad teeth.
- No, you have great teeth.

10:35.718 --> 10:36.833
Those aren't just freckles.

10:37.137 --> 10:39.503
If you look closely, you can see Cassiopeia.

10:40.473 --> 10:42.429
- What?
- Right there.

10:43.643 --> 10:44.632
Hold on a minute.

10:47.063 --> 10:48.269
Okay.

10:49.149 --> 10:51.140
All right.
Here's the story:

10:51.317 --> 10:54.104
A long time ago in Ethiopia,

10:54.112 --> 10:56.603
there was this queen named Cassiopeia,

10:56.614 --> 11:00.653
who thought she was the most
beautiful woman in the entire world,

11:00.660 --> 11:03.197
and there wasn't anybody in the kingdom
who wasn't offended

11:03.204 --> 11:05.536
by this woman's relentless vanity.

11:05.832 --> 11:08.448
And then one day, she really
screwed up and offended the gods.

11:08.459 --> 11:09.369
I don't remember what she did

11:09.377 --> 11:10.457
and I don't remember who she offended.

11:10.461 --> 11:12.292
But it was bad.
She crossed the line.

11:12.589 --> 11:14.830
But anyway, Poseidon, the sea god,

11:15.383 --> 11:18.295
punished Cassiopeia
by placing her in the heavens

11:18.303 --> 11:19.793
upside down in her throne,

11:20.305 --> 11:22.717
stuck for eternity with her skirt
around her shoulders,

11:22.724 --> 11:24.214
and all the blood rushing to her head.

11:25.185 --> 11:27.676
And now she's just a constellation in the sky,

11:28.897 --> 11:31.639
a bunch of English freckles
in the shape of a throne.

11:33.902 --> 11:35.813
So she made one tragic mistake.

11:38.072 --> 11:39.653
And paid for eternity.

11:40.033 --> 11:41.273
Correct.

12:01.095 --> 12:02.676
- Yeah, yeah, yeah.
- Legible, legible.

12:03.514 --> 12:04.799
I can't believe I'm doing this.

12:04.807 --> 12:07.173
Now, please, please.
Let fate take its proper course.

12:14.442 --> 12:15.352
Oh! Oh!

12:20.031 --> 12:22.272
That was an accident.
Write down that again, please.

12:22.283 --> 12:24.615
I can't.
That was a sign.

12:25.119 --> 12:26.450
Fate's telling us to back off.

12:27.580 --> 12:28.865
If fate didn't want us to be together,

12:28.873 --> 12:31.285
then why did we meet tonight, huh?
Gotcha.

12:31.751 --> 12:34.458
Well, I don't know, but it's not
an exact science. It's a feeling.

12:34.462 --> 12:35.577
Well, what if you're wrong, huh?

12:35.588 --> 12:37.453
What if it's all in our hands
and we just walk away?

12:37.465 --> 12:38.955
No names, no phone numbers, nothing.

12:38.967 --> 12:40.332
What do you think’s gonna happen?

12:40.343 --> 12:42.208
Do you think good old fate
is just gonna deliver my information

12:42.220 --> 12:43.209
right to your doorstep?

12:43.221 --> 12:45.303
Do you know that's the best idea
you've had all night?

12:45.723 --> 12:48.180
- What's the best...
- Here you go.

12:48.726 --> 12:49.806
Write your name and number down.

12:49.811 --> 12:51.927
- On a $5.00 bill?
- Mm. Just do it.

12:54.941 --> 12:57.899
You are a strange and interesting woman.

13:00.613 --> 13:01.523
Now what?

13:02.615 --> 13:03.775
Wait there.

13:16.379 --> 13:17.334
Hey!

13:20.091 --> 13:20.921
What the hell was that?

13:21.926 --> 13:24.588
When that $5.00 bill makes its way
back into my hands,

13:24.595 --> 13:25.801
I'll be able to call you.

13:25.805 --> 13:28.091
And when you hear my voice on the other end,

13:28.099 --> 13:29.805
then you'll believe in fate, won't you?

13:29.809 --> 13:32.095
♫ <i>Joy to the World</i>

13:32.770 --> 13:34.761
Hey, what about me?

13:35.106 --> 13:36.016
What do you mean?

13:36.024 --> 13:37.434
Well, we have to send something
out in the universe

13:37.442 --> 13:38.557
with your name on it, don't we?

13:38.568 --> 13:39.774
Come on.
Isn't that the only fair thing?

13:39.777 --> 13:41.108
That Is the only fair thing.

13:41.112 --> 13:43.478
What have I got, even?
Ooh.

13:43.489 --> 13:44.854
No. I have a really good idea.

13:44.866 --> 13:46.026
- What?
- Okay.

13:47.785 --> 13:49.400
That's a lot of tuba.

13:49.412 --> 13:51.027
- Okay, see this book?
- Yeah.

13:52.040 --> 13:53.405
Okay, so when I get home tonight,

13:53.416 --> 13:55.498
I'm gonna write my name and number
inside this book.

13:55.501 --> 13:58.789
And then first thing tomorrow morning,
I'll sell it to a used-book store.

13:59.297 --> 14:01.162
Which one?
You're not gonna tell me.

14:01.174 --> 14:02.129
You're not gonna tell me.
Why not?

14:02.133 --> 14:04.169
Well, now, every time you go past
an old bookstore,

14:04.177 --> 14:05.792
you're gonna have to go inside
to see if it's there.

14:06.971 --> 14:08.427
This is just wrong.

14:08.431 --> 14:10.467
You don't just have the most
incredible night of your life

14:10.475 --> 14:11.510
with a perfect stranger

14:11.517 --> 14:13.053
and then leave it all to chance, do ya?

14:13.853 --> 14:14.763
Do ya?

14:16.439 --> 14:17.645
Come with me a second.

14:17.815 --> 14:19.476
What, are we gonna get a room?

14:20.026 --> 14:22.483
I'm kidding.
But I wanna know you more.

14:22.487 --> 14:25.103
Come on. Where are we going?

14:25.114 --> 14:26.854
- Okay. Now, you stay here.
- Okay.

14:27.867 --> 14:29.448
No, stay here. Stay there.

14:29.452 --> 14:31.067
Don't make me come over there.

14:31.329 --> 14:32.318
- Okay.
- Okay.

14:32.330 --> 14:35.037
Right, if we both randomly pick the same floor,

14:35.041 --> 14:35.996
we're meant to be together now.

14:36.000 --> 14:37.240
You're insane.

14:38.586 --> 14:39.575
Come on.

14:40.588 --> 14:41.452
Okay, get in...

14:42.131 --> 14:43.166
take a breath,

14:43.174 --> 14:44.505
and then when the door closes, hit a button.

14:44.509 --> 14:45.874
I don't understand this.

14:45.885 --> 14:48.251
You don't have to understand.
You just have to have faith.

14:48.262 --> 14:49.251
Filth in what?

14:50.681 --> 14:51.966
Destiny.

14:52.308 --> 14:53.673
Oh. Here.

14:55.978 --> 14:56.933
Hey!

14:58.314 --> 14:59.303
It's Sara.

15:00.400 --> 15:01.515
My name's Sara.

15:33.933 --> 15:36.219
And here it is.
See? You were right.

15:36.227 --> 15:39.390
- Uh...
- Let's go, buddy.

15:40.148 --> 15:42.184
- We're going up here.
- Oh, that's okay.

15:42.191 --> 15:43.271
Josh likes to ride either way.

15:43.276 --> 15:45.608
- Don't you, Josh?
- Arrrrr!

15:45.611 --> 15:47.818
Don't do that!
Don't touch those!

15:47.822 --> 15:50.404
Hey, calm down.
He's just a kid.

16:04.547 --> 16:06.629
Looks like we've stopped.

16:09.927 --> 16:11.087
Ayah!

16:21.481 --> 16:24.894
- Oh. We're going again.
- Thank you.

16:26.777 --> 16:27.983
Where is she? Is she here?

16:27.987 --> 16:29.978
No, no. I don't think so.

16:29.989 --> 16:31.570
Come on, Josh.
Let's go, buddy.

16:38.873 --> 16:40.329
- Okay, stay alert.

16:42.627 --> 16:43.833
- Is she here?
- No, not here.

16:43.836 --> 16:45.201
- Back in the elevator.
- She's not here?

16:45.213 --> 16:47.750
Come on! Come on! Move it!
Come on, boy!

17:37.431 --> 17:39.262
Hey, Sara.
Oh, I'm sorry.

17:39.267 --> 17:41.883
- Hey. I'm sorry.
- What?

17:44.981 --> 17:46.061
I'm sorry.

18:36.657 --> 18:39.023
Usually, I have to beg to be a part of weddings.

18:39.035 --> 18:40.195
And If I do get into the wedding,

18:40.202 --> 18:43.285
of course, they've postponed it
and it's overseas somewhere,

18:43.289 --> 18:45.871
and they've canceled my passport
and I can't be a part of it,

18:45.875 --> 18:47.411
and it's ridiculous and all for naught.

18:47.543 --> 18:50.000
Well, thank you.
I take this very seriously.

18:50.004 --> 18:51.915
It's a gift to be the best man.

18:54.175 --> 18:55.335
They say that once in your lifetime,

18:55.343 --> 18:58.380
someone comes along whom
you're absolutely meant to be with.

18:58.763 --> 19:01.129
Everything feels great, stars are aligned,

19:01.515 --> 19:03.130
body and spirit are In balance.

19:03.684 --> 19:05.845
For my friend Jonathan Trager,

19:05.853 --> 19:07.138
that person...

19:07.146 --> 19:08.135
was me.

19:10.775 --> 19:12.857
But as you know, Jonny and I were simpatico.

19:12.860 --> 19:14.270
We were brothers from another mother.

19:14.278 --> 19:16.519
We were friends since freshman year.

19:16.781 --> 19:18.737
I watched him go out with woman after woman,

19:18.741 --> 19:21.153
and he'd always come crawling...

19:21.494 --> 19:23.109
He would come crawling back to me.

19:23.829 --> 19:25.035
It was embarrassing.

19:25.289 --> 19:26.244
You loved it.

19:26.248 --> 19:29.331
But then one night he came home
and things were different.

19:29.335 --> 19:31.667
His adolescent dream of becoming
a documentary filmmaker

19:31.671 --> 19:32.535
was a thing of the past.

19:32.546 --> 19:33.706
Thank God.

19:34.674 --> 19:38.417
He hardly even responded to my playful
yet tormenting flicks of my finger

19:38.427 --> 19:39.667
against the soft part of his skull

19:40.137 --> 19:41.343
as he studied for finals.

19:42.723 --> 19:45.465
And that is because he had found her:

19:45.476 --> 19:47.307
the woman he was meant to be with.

19:47.853 --> 19:50.845
And if anyone is qualified to know
when he met his soul mate,

19:50.856 --> 19:51.845
it would be me,

19:52.233 --> 19:53.268
his first wife.

19:56.821 --> 19:59.528
She's smart, she's funny, she's beautiful.

19:59.532 --> 20:02.274
In short, she's the kind of woman
that any man would dream about.

20:02.284 --> 20:03.444
And I think we all have.

20:03.452 --> 20:05.943
So it is with sadness

20:06.539 --> 20:08.951
and fond, fond memories,

20:08.958 --> 20:10.414
that I raise my glass

20:10.418 --> 20:12.784
to the new Mrs. Jonathan Trager.

20:12.795 --> 20:13.830
- Aww.
- Hear, hear.

20:13.838 --> 20:15.044
I'll tell you what.

20:15.756 --> 20:18.122
I'll tell you something. my friends,
if I had to lose Jonny to anyone,

20:18.134 --> 20:21.877
I can't imagine a more perfect
woman than Halley.

20:21.887 --> 20:22.797
- To Halley.

20:22.805 --> 20:24.090
Cheers to both of you.

20:30.271 --> 20:32.637
How drunk is he on a scale of one to ten?

20:32.648 --> 20:33.603
Twelve.

20:34.150 --> 20:36.391
You think we'll ever out-romance
Dean and Courtney?

20:36.402 --> 20:38.142
I don't know. I don't think
I've ever seen them fight.

20:38.154 --> 20:39.064
Me neither.

20:39.071 --> 20:40.652
Must be a bitch on their sex life.

20:40.656 --> 20:44.023
We... We have a pomegranate souffle,
which is amazing,

20:44.034 --> 20:45.490
which is different than the sorbet.

20:47.705 --> 20:50.447
Listen, we'd love to join you guys,
but Courtney has to wake up,

20:50.458 --> 20:52.824
so I got to be good.

20:52.835 --> 20:54.996
Halley, listen to me.
It's not too late to back out.

20:55.004 --> 20:56.995
- And I'm up... I'm up 116...
- Good night, Dean.

20:59.800 --> 21:03.042
Mama, you don't want to see this,
but I need... I need to snuggle.

21:03.053 --> 21:05.465
I'm gonna sleep it off.
Listen, you're wonderful.

21:05.473 --> 21:07.338
- Good night.
- You know what? You need me.

21:07.641 --> 21:09.051
Take care. Come on, hon.

21:09.059 --> 21:12.802
You guys, listen, I hate to tell you,
but I gotta go home too.

21:12.813 --> 21:14.098
- I have to.
- Come in for one drink.

21:14.106 --> 21:15.721
I gotta get up at 8:00 in the morning.
My day is crazy tomorrow.

21:15.733 --> 21:16.893
- Come in for one drink.
- He doesn't want to come.

21:16.901 --> 21:19.313
- He doesn't have to come.
- I'll see you in about 20 hours.

21:19.612 --> 21:20.647
- Bye-bye, dear.
- Good night.

21:20.654 --> 21:21.814
- I love you, son.
- Night-night.

21:21.822 --> 21:22.982
- George.
- Take care.

21:23.157 --> 21:24.192
- Good night.
- Take care.

21:24.992 --> 21:26.027
You okay?

21:27.620 --> 21:30.111
- You better be up later.
- Yeah, why?

21:30.122 --> 21:31.908
- Because I'm gonna come home and...
- Uh-huh.

21:31.916 --> 21:33.406
get undressed...

21:33.417 --> 21:35.123
- ...climb into bed...
- Uh-huh.

21:35.294 --> 21:37.706
act like we just got over a terrible fight.

21:40.633 --> 21:41.793
Cab!

21:44.094 --> 21:45.254
See you later now.

22:02.905 --> 22:04.065
Buy a book.

22:04.740 --> 22:06.947
Reading is good for you.
Knowledge.

22:11.831 --> 22:12.786
Read it?

22:25.511 --> 22:27.001
Hold on, hold on.
Listen, listen.

22:27.012 --> 22:28.127
I read it.
I read it a long time ago.

22:28.138 --> 22:30.345
I'll throw in the screenplay
to the <i>Bridges of Madison County.</i>

22:30.349 --> 22:32.556
- I saw the movie. It was great.
- I know you like that.

22:45.948 --> 22:46.937
Okay, and...

22:48.284 --> 22:49.945
And nothing. I mean...

22:49.952 --> 22:53.160
I mean, I did nothing.
I... I just let her walk out of the party

22:53.163 --> 22:54.653
and I didn't say anything to her.

22:54.665 --> 22:57.327
And now she's gone forever.

22:57.793 --> 23:01.206
I mean, she was my soul mate.

23:02.423 --> 23:05.540
Kenny, I honestly think it's dangerous
to use the term "soul mate."

23:06.260 --> 23:09.423
It implies there's some magical element
that we have no control over,

23:09.430 --> 23:11.045
like fate or destiny.

23:11.765 --> 23:15.303
I think holding onto beliefs like that
stops us doing the real work.

23:16.270 --> 23:18.556
And the fact is,
if your therapy here stays on track,

23:18.564 --> 23:20.395
I think you'll find there are
many, many people out there

23:20.399 --> 23:21.809
you could easily be happy with.

23:21.817 --> 23:23.648
You truly believe all that, Sara?

23:25.321 --> 23:27.903
Yeah.
I really do.

23:31.076 --> 23:33.567
- There you go.
- Thanks.

